) [73–75], were calculated and reported in Table 3. The calculations indicate that the μ value for HBC-FU1, HBC-FU2, BN-FU1, BP-FU1 and AlN-FU1 complexes decreases after adsorption of the drug, whereas for BP-FU2, AlN-FU2, AlP-FU1 and AlP-FU2 complexes it increases. The global hardness represents the resistance to the electron cloud change of the chemical system, and can determine the stability of species. The small values of HOMO-LUMO energy gap, hardness and chemical potential are associated with high chemical reactivity. Our results indicate that the global hardness for GQDs decreases after adsorption of FU drug and only a increase is seen upon adsorption of drug on BP and AlP GQD in BP-FU2 and AlP-FU1 complexes. The global electrophilicity index indicates the global electrophilic nature of a molecule within a relative scale. The large value of ω is associated with high chemical reactivity. As can be seen from Table 3, the AlN-FU and AlP-FU complexes have the smallest HOMO-LUMO energy gaps, chemical potentials and global hardnesses as well as the greatest electrophilicity index. These results indicate that the AlN-FU and AlP-FU complexes have high chemical reactivity, which is crucial for their attachments to the target site. Consequently, AlN and AlP GQDs are potential carrier candidates to deliver the FU drug into the target site.

The nature of interactions between FU drug and GQDs are analyzed in terms of the electron density (ρb) and its Laplacian (∇2ρb), kinetic electron energy density (Gb), potential electron energy density (Vb), total electron energy density (Hb) and −Gb/Vb ratio (see Fig. 6
                         and Table 4
                        ). The electron density at a BCP is related to the strength of a interaction [76]. As seen from Table 4, the sum of electron density values at the BCPs of AlN-FU and AlP-FU complexes larger than that in HBC-FU, BN-FU and BP-FU complexes. The plot of adsorption energy versus the sum of electron density values (Σρb) at the BCPs formed between FU drug and GQDs exhibit good linear relationship with correlation coefficients (R2) of 0.8091 (see Fig. 7
                        ). It is observed that a larger Σρb value at the BCP results in a lower Ead value. The values of ∇2ρb are all positive, in a range of 0.0143–0.4565 au. The positive value of Laplacian of electron densities denotes depletion of electronic charge density in the interatomic surface. A negative value of total electron energy density (Hb = Gb + Vb) implies a shared interaction (covalent nature), and a positive value of Hb indicate a closed-shell interaction. Moreover, −Gb/Vb < 1 indicate a covalent nature of the interaction, whereas −Gb/Vb > 1 are indicative of the noncovalent interactions. The calculations show that for all BCPs (except for BCP-2 AlN-FU1 and BCP-2 AlN-FU2), ∇2ρb > 0, Hb > 0 and −Gb/Vb > 1, which indicate that these interactions are of “closed-shell” noncovalent nature. For BCP-2 AlN-FU1 and BCP-2 AlN-FU2, ∇2ρb > 0, Hb < 0 and −Gb/Vb < 1, which infer that these interactions are partially covalent and partially electrostatic.
